#Text=Published , September , 1908

#Text=The neighbourhood of Bloomsbury Square towards four o’clock of a November afternoon is not so crowded as to secure to the stranger , of appearance anything out of the common , immunity from observation .

#Text=Tibb ’s boy , screaming at the top of his voice that she was his honey , stopped suddenly , stepped backwards on to the toes of a voluble young lady wheeling a perambulator , and remained deaf , apparently , to the somewhat personal remarks of the voluble young lady .

#Text=Not until he had reached the next corner -- and then more as a soliloquy than as information to the street -- did Tibb ’s boy recover sufficient interest in his own affairs to remark that he was her bee .
#Text=The voluble young lady herself , following some half-a-dozen yards behind , forgot her wrongs in contemplation of the stranger ’s back .
#Text=There was this that was peculiar about the stranger ’s back : that instead of being flat it presented a decided curve .
#Text=“ It ai n’t a ‘ ump , and it do n’t look like kervitcher of the spine , ” observed the voluble young lady to herself .
#Text=“ Blimy if I do n’t believe ‘ e ’s taking ‘ ome ‘ is washing up his back . ”
#Text=The constable at the corner , trying to seem busy doing nothing , noticed the stranger ’s approach with gathering interest .
#Text=“ That ’s an odd sort of a walk of yours , young man , ” thought the constable .
#Text=“ You take care you do n’t fall down and tumble over yourself . ”
#Text=“ Thought he was a young man , ” murmured the constable , the stranger having passed him . “ He had a young face right enough . ”
#Text=The daylight was fading .
#Text=The stranger , finding it impossible to read the name of the street upon the corner house , turned back .
#Text=“ Why , ‘ tis a young man , ” the constable told himself ; “ a mere boy . ”
#Text=“ I beg your pardon , ” said the stranger ;
#Text=“ but would you mind telling me my way to Bloomsbury Square . ”
#Text=“ This is Bloomsbury Square , ” explained the constable ;
#Text=“ leastways round the corner is .
#Text=What number might you be wanting ? ”
#Text=The stranger took from the ticket pocket of his tightly buttoned overcoat a piece of paper , unfolded it and read it out :
#Text=“ Mrs. Pennycherry .
#Text=Number Forty-eight . ”
#Text=“ Round to the left , ” instructed him the constable ; “ fourth house .
#Text=Been recommended there ? ”
#Text=“ By -- by a friend , ” replied the stranger .
#Text=“ Thank you very much . ”
#Text=“ Ah , ” muttered the constable to himself ;
#Text=“ guess you wo n’t be calling him that by the end of the week , young -- ”
#Text=“ Funny , ” added the constable , gazing after the retreating figure of the stranger .
#Text=“ Seen plenty of the other sex as looked young behind and old in front .
#Text=This cove looks young in front and old behind .
#Text=Guess he ’ll look old all round if he stops long at mother Pennycherry ’s : stingy old cat . ”
#Text=Constables whose beat included Bloomsbury Square had their reasons for not liking Mrs. Pennycherry .
#Text=Indeed it might have been difficult to discover any human being with reasons for liking that sharp-featured lady .
#Text=Maybe the keeping of second-rate boarding houses in the neighbourhood of Bloomsbury does not tend to develop the virtues of generosity and amiability .
#Text=Meanwhile the stranger , proceeding upon his way , had rung the bell of Number Forty-eight .

#Text=Mrs. Pennycherry , peeping from the area and catching a glimpse , above the railings , of a handsome if somewhat effeminate masculine face , hastened to readjust her widow ’s cap before the looking-glass while directing Mary Jane to show the stranger , should he prove a problematical boarder , into the dining-room , and to light the gas .
#Text=“ And do n’t stop gossiping , and do n’t you take it upon yourself to answer questions .
#Text=Say I ’ll be up in a minute , ” were Mrs. Pennycherry ’s further instructions , “ and mind you hide your hands as much as you can . ”
#Text=***
#Text=“ What are you grinning at ? ” demanded Mrs. Pennycherry , a couple of minutes later , of the dingy Mary Jane .
#Text=“ Was n’t grinning , ” explained the meek Mary Jane , “ was only smiling to myself . ”
#Text=“ What at ? ”
#Text=“ Dunno , ” admitted Mary Jane .
#Text=But still she went on smiling .
#Text=“ What ’s he like then ? ” demanded Mrs. Pennycherry .
#Text=“ ‘ E ai n’t the usual sort , ” was Mary Jane ’s opinion .
#Text=“ Thank God for that , ” ejaculated Mrs. Pennycherry piously .
#Text=“ Says ‘ e ’s been recommended , by a friend . ”
#Text=“ By whom ? ”
#Text=“ By a friend . ‘ E did n’t say no name . ” Mrs. Pennycherry pondered .
#Text=“ He ’s not the funny sort , is he ? ”
#Text=Not that sort at all .
#Text=Mary Jane was sure of it .
#Text=Mrs. Pennycherry ascended the stairs still pondering .
#Text=As she entered the room the stranger rose and bowed .
#Text=Nothing could have been simpler than the stranger ’s bow , yet there came with it to Mrs. Pennycherry a rush of old sensations long forgotten .
#Text=For one brief moment Mrs. Pennycherry saw herself an amiable well-bred lady , widow of a solicitor : a visitor had called to see her .
#Text=It was but a momentary fancy .
#Text=The next instant Reality reasserted itself .

#Text=Mrs. Pennycherry , a lodging-house keeper , existing precariously upon a daily round of petty meannesses , was prepared for contest with a possible new boarder , who fortunately looked an inexperienced young gentleman .
#Text=“ Someone has recommended me to you , ” began Mrs. Pennycherry ; “ may I ask who ? ”
#Text=But the stranger waved the question aside as immaterial .
#Text=“ You might not remember -- him , ” he smiled .
#Text=“ He thought that I should do well to pass the few months I am given -- that I have to be in London , here .
#Text=You can take me in ? ”
#Text=Mrs. Pennycherry thought that she would be able to take the stranger in .
#Text=“ A room to sleep in , ” explained the stranger , “ -- any room will do -- with food and drink sufficient for a man , is all that I require . ”
